@crossroads1112, right now, if you remove `github.com` from your `~/.ssh/known_hosts`, you'll likely see a visual glitch whereby `Authenticating...` (https://github.com/cs50/submit50/blob/ssh/submit50.py#L431) disappears altogether for a split second (or longer, if network is slow), after which you see `ssh`'s prompt to accept `github.com`'s certificate, the reason being I deliberately call `spin(False)` at https://github.com/cs50/submit50/blob/ssh/submit50.py#L439 so that the spinner doesn't keep spinning once `ssh` starts outputting `stdout` via `call`. Ideally, though, I'd only like `spin(False)` to get called once `ssh` has spit out >= 1 byte to `stdout`, else there's indeed a moment when there's no progress message on the screen. But, the `ssh` subprocess has to be interactive, so that the user can accept the server's certificate, if connecting via SSH to GitHub for the first time. Can you think of a relatively clean way to eliminate the glitch? Perhaps using `subprocess.Popen` and listening for the first byte written to `stdout` before calling `spin(False)`, while simultaneously allowing for `stdin` so that the user can be prompted to type `yes` or `no` one or more times?

